    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/4903725694/lesson-105-the-past-imperfect-tense" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="Today we&rsquo;re going to learn all about yet another tense in Hindi, The Past Imperfect Tense! So firstly, what is the Past Imperfect Tense? Well it&rsquo;s simple, in English it&rsquo;s sentences that include &lsquo;used to&rsquo;. It shows something used to happen in the past and doesn&rsquo;t happen anymore. For example we might say &ldquo;I used to eat meat&rdquo;, &ldquo;We used to play cricket&rdquo; etc etc. Don&rsquo;t worry though, you&rsquo;ll see plenty of examples as we go through! As usual there&rsquo;s a few questions at the end of the lesson to check you&rsquo;ve understood everything!&nbsp;


 Now can you remember back to Lesson #28: The Present Tense? The Past Imperfect Tense is actually very similar to The Present Tense! Let me show you an example! We know how to say 'I live in India&rsquo;, (using the verb &#2352;&#2361;&#2344;&#2366; rahnaa - To Live) we just say&hellip;





&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2349;&#2366;&#2352;&#2340; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2352;&#2361;&#2340;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main bhaarat men rahtaa hoon  - I live in India (Said by a Male)


 This is in the Present Tense, so how do we change it to the Past Imperfect? It&rsquo;s easy, we simply change the &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; hoon - am to the correct 'version&rsquo; of &#2341;&#2366; thaa - was! (As we learnt in Lesson #69). So we&rsquo;d say&hellip;


&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2349;&#2366;&#2352;&#2340; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2352;&#2361;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366; main bhaarat men rahtaa thaa - I used to live in India (Said by a Male)


 Can you see the difference? &#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366; acchaa - Great! Ready for another example? Do you remember how we say &ldquo;She writes stories&rdquo;, that&rsquo;s right, we say&hellip;





&#2357;&#2361; &#2325;&#2361;&#2366;&#2344;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305; &#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2340;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376; voh kahaaniyaan likhtee hai - She writes stories


 So how would we change this to The Past Imperfect Tense? So it says &ldquo;She used to write stories&rdquo; instead? That&rsquo;s right, we say&hellip;


&#2357;&#2361; &#2325;&#2361;&#2366;&#2344;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305; &#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2340;&#2368; &#2341;&#2368; voh kahaaniyaan likhtee thee&nbsp; - She use to write stories


 Remember that we use &#2341;&#2368; thee - 'was&rsquo; here because the subject (she) is feminine!


 So all you need to remember for the Past Imperfect Tense is that we use the normal Present Tense and then we drop the &#2361;&#2376; hai, &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; hain or &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;  hoon&nbsp;from the end and instead add one of&nbsp;&#2341;&#2366; thaa, &#2341;&#2375; the, &#2341;&#2368;  thee or &#2341;&#2368;&#2306; theen&nbsp;depending on the subject of the sentence! Told you it was easy! Ready for another example?&nbsp;





&#2358;&#2344;&#2367;&#2357;&#2366;&#2352; &#2325;&#2379; &#2361;&#2350; &#2340;&#2376;&#2352;&#2340;&#2375; &#2341;&#2375; shanivaar ko ham tairte the - On saturdays we used to swim.


 Can you remember the word &#2358;&#2344;&#2367;&#2357;&#2366;&#2352; shanivaar - Saturday from Lesson #91? And then we&rsquo;ve just used &#2361;&#2350; &#2340;&#2376;&#2352;&#2340;&#2375; &#2341;&#2375; ham tairte the - We used to swim. Are you getting the hang of it?&nbsp;


 Ready for another example? How would we say 'He used to study German&rsquo;? The word for German (as in the language) is &#2332;&#2352;&#2381;&#2360;&#2344; &#2349;&#2366;&#2359;&#2366; jarman bhaasaa. So we&rsquo;d say&hellip;





&#2357;&#2361; &#2332;&#2352;&#2381;&#2350;&#2344; &#2349;&#2366;&#2359;&#2366; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366;  voh jarman bhaasaa parhtaa thaa   - He used to study German


 Finally for today then, when you want to use the Past Imperfect Tense with an adjective, for example saying 'I used to be short&rsquo;, or &nbsp;'They used to be very fat&rsquo; you still drop the &#2361;&#2376; hai, &#2361;&#2376;&#2306; hain or &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;  hoon from the end of the sentence, but then you add either &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2366; hotaa, &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2375;&nbsp;hote&nbsp;or &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2368;&nbsp;hotee before the &#2341;&#2366; thaa, &#2341;&#2375; the, &#2341;&#2368;  thee or &#2341;&#2368;&#2306; theen! Does that make sence? Let me show you an example, we know how to say 'I am fat&rsquo; (said by a male), it&rsquo;s just&hellip;





&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2350;&#2379;&#2335;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305; main motaa hoon - I am fat (Said by a Male)


 So to change this to 'I used to be fat&rsquo;, just as I said just above, we simply drop the&nbsp;&#2361;&#2370;&#2305; hoon and add  &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366; hotaa thaa to give&hellip;


&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2350;&#2379;&#2335;&#2366; &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366; main motaa hotaa thaa - I used to be fat (Said by a Male)


 So one last example for today! How would you say 'You used to be tall&rsquo; to a female? That&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s simply&hellip;





&#2340;&#2369;&#2350; &#2354;&#2306;&#2348;&#2368; &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2368; &#2341;&#2368;&#2306; tum lambee hotee theen - You used to be tall (To a Female)


 Remember that&nbsp; &#2340;&#2369;&#2350; tum is always treated as plural so we have to use&nbsp;&#2341;&#2368;&#2306; theen! Have you understood everything today? Hopefully! Feel free to leave me a comment with a question if you&rsquo;re confused by anything! Do you think you can try and answer the five questions below? Just give a go, even if you&rsquo;re not sure. I&rsquo;m here to help! Leave your answers or guesses in a comment below and I&rsquo;ll let you know how well you did&hellip;


 
 I used to learn Hindi (Said by a Female)


 We used to drink tea&nbsp;


 He used to sing on Mondays (Remember To Sing is &#2327;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366; gaanaa and see&nbsp;Lesson #91)


 I used to love you (Said by a male; See Lesson #29 for help!)


 We used to be clever (Remember: Clever - &#2361;&#2379;&#2358;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2352; hoshiyaar)



 Leave your answers in a comment below and I&rsquo;ll let you know how well you&rsquo;ve done! And remember feel free to ask me if you have any questions at all!&nbsp;


 Back to Beginners Grammar." property="og:description" /><meta content="Lesson #105: The Past Imperfect Tense" property="og:title" /><style type="text/css">p.center { text-align: center; }

