                     --><!-- <li><a class="label" href="/ask" id="ask">Ask me anything!</a></li> --><li><a class="label" href="../../intro"><small> - Introduction</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../vowels"><small>- Vowels</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../consonants"><small>- Consonants</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../convo"><small>- Conversational</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../beginner"><small> - Beginner's</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../intermediate"><small> - Intermediate</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../numbers"><small> - Numbers</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../urdu"><small> - Urdu</small></a></li><li><a class="label" href="../../all"><small> - All Lessons</small></a></li><!--  <li class="galleries"><div class="label">Lessons</div><div class="menu-wrap"><ul class="menu"><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/intro">Introduction</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/vowels">Vowels</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/consonants">Consonants</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/convo">Conversational</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/beginner">Beginner's Grammar</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/intermediate">Intermediate</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/numbers">Numbers</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/urdu">Urdu</a></li><li><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/all">All Lessons</a></li></ul></div></li><li id="search"><div class="label">Search<div class="icon"></div></div><div class="form-wrap"><div class="icon"></div><form action="/search" id="search-form" method="get"><input id="search-field" name="q" onblur="if (this.value == '') {this.value = 'Search tags';}" onfocus="if (this.value == 'Search tags') {this.value = '';}" type="text" value="Search tags" /></form></div></li> --><li><a class="label" href="../../legal">Legal</a> </li><li><a class="label" href="../../links">Links</a> </li> 

          </ul></div><div id="posts"><article class="post type-text" id="4903725694"><aside class="metadata not-custom-page"><a class="timestamp" href="lesson-105-the-past-imperfect-tense">April 24th, 2011</a><!--  
                               <a class="note-count" href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/4903725694/lesson-105-the-past-imperfect-tense#notes">3 notes</a> --><a class="comment-count" href="lesson-105-the-past-imperfect-tense#disqus_thread"></a><script type="text/javascript">
    var disqus_shortname = 'learninghindi';

    (function () {
        var s = document.createElement('script'); s.async = true;
        s.type = 'text/javascript';
        s.src = '//' + disqus_shortname + '.disqus.com/count.js';
        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-105-the-past-imperfect-tense">Lesson #105: The Past Imperfect Tense</a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Today we&rsquo;re going to learn all about yet another tense in Hindi, The Past Imperfect Tense! So firstly, what is the Past Imperfect Tense? Well it&rsquo;s simple, in English it&rsquo;s sentences that include &lsquo;used to&rsquo;. It shows something used to happen in the past and doesn&rsquo;t happen anymore. For example we might say &ldquo;I used to eat meat&rdquo;, &ldquo;We used to play cricket&rdquo; etc etc. Don&rsquo;t worry though, you&rsquo;ll see plenty of examples as we go through! As usual there&rsquo;s a few questions at the end of the lesson to check you&rsquo;ve understood everything!&nbsp;</p><p>Now can you remember back to <a href="../938215810/lesson-28-verbs-part-2-the-present-tense">Lesson #28: The Present Tense</a>? The Past Imperfect Tense is actually very similar to The Present Tense! Let me show you an example! We know how to say 'I live in India&rsquo;, (using the verb <big><big>&#2352;&#2361;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>rahnaa</em> - To Live) we just say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/68eeb3beebd33a7cac399c12a0d5459e/tumblr_inline_mnfj3uAzJp1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2349;&#2366;&#2352;&#2340; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2352;&#2361;&#2340;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <br><em>main bhaarat men rahtaa hoon</em><br> - I live in India (Said by a Male)</p><p>This is in the Present Tense, so how do we change it to the Past Imperfect? It&rsquo;s easy, we simply change the <big><big>&#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>hoon</em> - am to the correct 'version&rsquo; of <big><big>&#2341;&#2366;</big></big> <em>thaa</em> - was! (As we learnt in <a href="../1518014000/lesson-69-past-tense-part-1-was-and-were">Lesson #69</a>). So we&rsquo;d say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2349;&#2366;&#2352;&#2340; &#2350;&#2375;&#2306; &#2352;&#2361;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366;</big></big> <br><em>main bhaarat men rahtaa thaa</em><br>- I used to live in India (Said by a Male)</p><p>Can you see the difference? <big><big>&#2309;&#2330;&#2381;&#2331;&#2366;</big></big> <em>acchaa</em> - Great! Ready for another example? Do you remember how we say &ldquo;She writes stories&rdquo;, that&rsquo;s right, we say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/2a541b87e7a0a4b2c656e5b8236d6c9b/tumblr_inline_mnfj4rv4MT1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2357;&#2361; &#2325;&#2361;&#2366;&#2344;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305; &#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2340;&#2368; &#2361;&#2376;</big></big> <br><em>voh kahaaniyaan likhtee hai</em> <br>- She writes stories</p><p>So how would we change this to The Past Imperfect Tense? So it says &ldquo;She used to write stories&rdquo; instead? That&rsquo;s right, we say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2357;&#2361; &#2325;&#2361;&#2366;&#2344;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2305; &#2354;&#2367;&#2326;&#2340;&#2368; &#2341;&#2368;</big></big> <br><em>voh kahaaniyaan likhtee thee</em>&nbsp;<br>- She use to write stories</p><p>Remember that we use <big><big>&#2341;&#2368;</big></big> <em>thee</em> - 'was&rsquo; here because the subject (she) is feminine!</p><p>So all you need to remember for the Past Imperfect Tense is that we use the normal Present Tense and then we drop the <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;</big></big> <em>hai</em>, <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big> <em>hain</em> or <big><big>&#2361;&#2370;&#2305; </big></big> <em>hoon</em>&nbsp;from the end and instead add one of&nbsp;<big><big>&#2341;&#2366;</big></big> <em>thaa</em>, <big><big>&#2341;&#2375;</big></big> <em>the</em>, <big><big>&#2341;&#2368; </big></big> <em>thee</em> or <big><big>&#2341;&#2368;&#2306;</big></big> <em>theen</em>&nbsp;depending on the subject of the sentence! Told you it was easy! Ready for another example?&nbsp;</p><p class="center"><img src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/ca45eed54ff1dc6f452ee777a5a6bdc9/tumblr_inline_mnfj5gQCD61qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2358;&#2344;&#2367;&#2357;&#2366;&#2352; &#2325;&#2379; &#2361;&#2350; &#2340;&#2376;&#2352;&#2340;&#2375; &#2341;&#2375;</big></big> <em>shanivaar ko ham tairte the</em><br>- On saturdays we used to swim.</p><p>Can you remember the word <big><big>&#2358;&#2344;&#2367;&#2357;&#2366;&#2352;</big></big> <em>shanivaar</em> - Saturday from <a href="../3072325702/lesson-91-days-of-the-week">Lesson #91</a>? And then we&rsquo;ve just used <big><big>&#2361;&#2350; &#2340;&#2376;&#2352;&#2340;&#2375; &#2341;&#2375;</big></big> <em>ham tairte the</em> - We used to swim. Are you getting the hang of it?&nbsp;</p><p>Ready for another example? How would we say 'He used to study German&rsquo;? The word for German (as in the language) is <big><big>&#2332;&#2352;&#2381;&#2360;&#2344; &#2349;&#2366;&#2359;&#2366;</big></big> <em>jarman bhaasaa</em>. So we&rsquo;d say&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lk67kkkVEB1qzfx8l.jpg"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2357;&#2361; &#2332;&#2352;&#2381;&#2350;&#2344; &#2349;&#2366;&#2359;&#2366; &#2346;&#2338;&#2364;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366;<br></big></big> <em>voh jarman bhaasaa parhtaa thaa </em><br> - He used to study German</p><p>Finally for today then, when you want to use the Past Imperfect Tense with an adjective, for example saying 'I used to be short&rsquo;, or &nbsp;'They used to be very fat&rsquo; you still drop the <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;</big></big> <em>hai</em>, <big><big>&#2361;&#2376;&#2306;</big></big> <em>hain</em> or <big><big>&#2361;&#2370;&#2305; </big></big> <em>hoon </em>from the end of the sentence, but then you add either <big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2366;</big></big> <em>hotaa</em>, <big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2375;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>hote</em>&nbsp;or <big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2368;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>hotee</em> before the <big><big>&#2341;&#2366;</big></big> <em>thaa</em>, <big><big>&#2341;&#2375;</big></big> <em>the</em>, <big><big>&#2341;&#2368; </big></big> <em>thee</em> or <big><big>&#2341;&#2368;&#2306;</big></big> <em>theen</em>! Does that make sence? Let me show you an example, we know how to say 'I am fat&rsquo; (said by a male), it&rsquo;s just&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/6da0c031ad7eaba38496ff540b1c38d5/tumblr_inline_mnfj6uIWbw1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2350;&#2379;&#2335;&#2366; &#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>main motaa hoon</em> <br>- I am fat (Said by a Male)</p><p>So to change this to 'I used to be fat&rsquo;, just as I said just above, we simply drop the&nbsp;<big><big>&#2361;&#2370;&#2305;</big></big> <em>hoon</em> and add <big><big> &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366;</big></big> <em>hotaa thaa</em> to give&hellip;</p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2350;&#2376;&#2306; &#2350;&#2379;&#2335;&#2366; &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2366; &#2341;&#2366;</big></big> <em>main motaa hotaa thaa <br></em>- I used to be fat (Said by a Male)</p><p>So one last example for today! How would you say 'You used to be tall&rsquo; to a female? That&rsquo;s right, it&rsquo;s simply&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/f2b1f116cfe412911dd66b8a2384e974/tumblr_inline_mnfj7bsfkl1qz4rgp.png"></p><p class="center"><big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350; &#2354;&#2306;&#2348;&#2368; &#2361;&#2379;&#2340;&#2368; &#2341;&#2368;&#2306;</big></big> <em>tum lambee hotee theen</em><br>- You used to be tall (To a Female)</p><p>Remember that&nbsp; <big><big>&#2340;&#2369;&#2350;</big></big> <em>tum</em> is always treated as plural so we have to use&nbsp;<big><big>&#2341;&#2368;&#2306;</big></big><em> theen</em>! Have you understood everything today? Hopefully! Feel free to leave me a comment with a question if you&rsquo;re confused by anything! Do you think you can try and answer the five questions below? Just give a go, even if you&rsquo;re not sure. I&rsquo;m here to help! Leave your answers or guesses in a comment below and I&rsquo;ll let you know how well you did&hellip;</p><ol><li>I used to learn Hindi (Said by a Female)</li><li>We used to drink tea&nbsp;</li><li>He used to sing on Mondays (Remember To Sing is <big><big>&#2327;&#2366;&#2344;&#2366;</big></big> <em>gaanaa </em>and see&nbsp;<a href="../3072325702/lesson-91-days-of-the-week">Lesson #91</a>)</li><li>I used to love you (Said by a male; See <a href="../963456550/lesson-29-i-love-you">Lesson #29</a> for help!)</li><li>We used to be clever (Remember: Clever - <big><big>&#2361;&#2379;&#2358;&#2367;&#2351;&#2366;&#2352;</big></big> <em>hoshiyaar</em>)</li></ol><p>Leave your answers in a comment below and I&rsquo;ll let you know how well you&rsquo;ve done! And remember feel free to ask me if you have any questions at all!&nbsp;</p><p><a href="../../beginner">Back to Beginners Grammar</a>.</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/apr2011">apr2011</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/grammar">grammar</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/past-imperfect">past imperfect</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/past-tense">past tense</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/urdu">urdu</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/india">india</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="4903725694" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_4903725694"><iframe id="like_iframe_4903725694" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=4903725694&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=8q61X0iI" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_4903725694"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/4